UNDIAGNOSED DEATHS, CAMELS - SAUDI ARABIA: REQUEST FOR INFORMATION (06)
***********************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[1]
Date: Thu 30 Aug 2007
Source: Dailystar, Lebanon, Agence France-Presse (AFP) report
[extracted, edited]
<http://www.dailystar.com.lb/article.asp?edition_ID=10&article_ID=84905&categ_id=2>

Saudi Arabia has sent frozen samples of dead camels to France to try
to discover why dozens are dying each day, along with cattle and
sheep, newspapers said on Wednesday [29 Aug 2007].
Al-Watan newspaper said 60 more camels died on Tuesday [28 Aug 2007]
as well as 400 sheep and 7 cows. There was no official confirmation
of the figures.
The camel samples were sent on Tuesday [28 Aug 2007], as Saudi
officials came under increasing criticism by owners of herds for not
acting more quickly to try to determine ways to tackle the problem.
On 25 Aug 2007, some 2 weeks after the beasts began to die,
Agriculture Minister Fahd bin Abdel-Rahman Balghnaim said nearly 2000
camels had died. "It is not because of an infectious disease. These
were cases of poisoning," the minister was quoted as saying by the
SPA state news agency.
Balghnaim said the animals were fed bran that had been bought from
traders whose bran stocks were contaminated. He put the final number
of dead camels in recent weeks at 1982.
Laboratory research was being carried out to reveal exactly what was
wrong with the animal feed, he said at the time.
According to figures in the Saudi press, at least 5000 camels have
now died and thousands more are sick. Official figures put the total
number of camels in the kingdom in 2005 at 862 000.
Just before the camels began to die, newspapers had reported an
outbreak of foot-&-mouth disease [FMD] -- which can also affect
camels -- in the kingdom. [FMD is generally regarded to be
subclinical in camels; its role in the syndrome described above seems
most unlikely. - Mod.AS]
